  "title": "The Cross Product",
  "body": " The Cross Product    Introducing the cross product.    In a previous section you learned about the dot product as one way to multiply vectors. Another way to multiply vectors is the cross product , named because you will use to represent the multiplication. Unlike the dot product, the cross product of two vectors is a vector , not a scalar.   The Cross Product   The magnitude of the cross product between two vectors is given by , where is the angle between the vectors when placed tail-to-tail. The direction is always perpendicular to both and , and is given by the right hand rule (see below).     A representation of vectors A and B and the angle between them illustrating the cross product for two vectors.    Here, represents the angle between the two vectors when they are placed tail to tail. A and B represent the magnitudes of the vectors and .    Introducing the right hand rule.     The Right Hand Rule   ADD FIGURE The direction of the vector that results from the cross product can be determined using the right hand rule . To use the right hand rule, align your thumb in the direction of , your index finger in the direction of vector , and your remaining fingers will point in the direction of vector .    Conceptually, the magnitude of the cross product quantifies how perpendicular two vectors are. The magnitude of the cross product is the magnitude of multiplied by the projection of perpendicular to . You can think of a projection as the length of the shadow that would cast perpendicular to if you were to shine a light from above.       Practice Activities   Indicate the direction of the cross product of the two vectors in the figure above, .  Into the screen!  Use the two vectors shown below for the remaining questions.       Indicate the direction of the cross product .    Label the appropriate angle and estimate its value. Use your estimate and the value for the magnitude of both vectors to estimate the magnitude of .    "
