  "number": "5.2",
  "title": "Centripetal Acceleration",
  "body": " Centripetal Acceleration  ADD ME Velocity for motion along a curved path.  When an object moves along a curved path, the instantaneous velocity always points tangent to the curve.   Model Application - Acceleration Direction  The figure below shows four different instants (A-D) for a car moving clockwise along a curved path at constant speed.    Three cases, each showing a car moving clockwise around a curved path, with points A and B far apart, A and C closer together, and A and D very close together.   Sketch vectors for the instantaneous velocity at each instant.  Sketch vectors for the change in velocity for each case.  Use the definition of instantaneous acceleration to determine the direction of the car's acceleration at instant A.   Determining the direction of centripetal acceleration.   Model Application - Acceleration Magnitude  The figure below shows three identical cars, each moving around a circular track. Cars A and B move at different constant speeds around tracks with the same radius. Cars A and C move at the same speed around tracks with different radius.    Three cases, each showing a car moving clockwise around a circular path of radius d. Car A moves at constant speed v, Car B moves at constant speed 2v, and Car C moves at constant speed v around a circle of radius d\/2.   Predict which of the three cars has an acceleration with the largest magnitude. Explain your reasoning  The figure below shows several instants for the cars described above. In each case, the two points are separated by the same distance along the path.    Three cases, each showing a car moving clockwise around a circular path of radius r. Car A moves at constant speed v, Car B moves at constant speed 2v, and Car C moves at constant speed v around a circle of radius r\/2.   Sketch vectors for the instantaneous velocity for each point.  Sketch vectors for the change in velocity for each case.  Use the definition of instantaneous acceleration to rank the magnitudes of the cars' accelerations.   Determining the magnitude of centripetal acceleration.   Centripetal Acceleration   An object moving along a curved path experiences a centripetal acceleration that points perpendicular to the path (inward) with magnitude , where is the local radius of curvature. If the object is moving at constant speed, the acceleration is entirely centripetal.    "
